Data import¶

Data were crawled from hockey-reference.com by our crawler. We uploaded the data to github, from where we're able to import them.

In [ ]:
csv_files = [
    'franchises.csv',
    'overtime.csv',
    'playoff.csv'
]

# Base URL of the GitHub repository
base_url = 'https://github.com/tadeaskaminsky/nhl_analysis/raw/main/'

# Dictionary to hold DataFrames
dataframes_fop = {}

# Loop through the list of CSV files and read each one into a DataFrame
for file_name in csv_files:
    file_url = base_url + file_name
    response = requests.get(file_url)

    if response.status_code == 200:
        # Read the CSV file into a DataFrame
        df = pd.read_csv(io.StringIO(response.text))

        # Set the index starting from 1
        df.index = range(1, len(df) + 1)

        # Extract the file name without extension to use as a key
        key_name = file_name.split('.')[0]

        # Store the DataFrame in the dictionary
        dataframes_fop[key_name] = df

# Access DataFrame for a specific file
for key, df in dataframes_fop.items():
    print(f"DataFrame for {key}:")
    print(df.head())  # Print the first few rows of each DataFrame

Slovakian players¶

In [ ]:
csv_files = [
    'utocnici_stats.csv',
    'obrancovia_stats.csv'
]

# Base URL of the GitHub repository
base_url = 'https://github.com/tadeaskaminsky/nhl_analysis/raw/main/'

# Dictionary to hold DataFrames
dataframes_slovakia = {}

# Loop through the list of CSV files and read each one into a DataFrame
for file_name in csv_files:
    file_url = base_url + file_name
    response = requests.get(file_url)

    if response.status_code == 200:
        # Read the CSV file into a DataFrame
        slovakian_players = pd.read_csv(io.StringIO(response.text))

        slovakian_players_no_nan = slovakian_players.dropna(axis=1, how='any')
        slovakian_players_no_nan = slovakian_players_no_nan.sort_values(by='Season')
        slovakian_players_no_nan.index = range(1, len(slovakian_players) + 1)

        # Extract the file name without extension to use as a key
        key_name = file_name.split('.')[0]

        # Store the DataFrame in the dictionary
        dataframes_slovakia[key_name] = slovakian_players_no_nan

for key, slovakian_players in dataframes_slovakia.items():
    print(f"DataFrame for {key}:")
    display(slovakian_players)
    print(slovakian_players.shape)

obrancovia = dataframes_slovakia['obrancovia_stats']
x_labels = ['1st Season', '2nd Season']
unique_players = obrancovia['Name'].unique()

fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 3, figsize=(30, 20))

for player in unique_players:
    player_data = obrancovia[obrancovia['Name'] == player]

    if len(player_data) == 1: # Fixing Nemec, he played only one season
        seasons = ['1st Season']
        goals = player_data['G'].values
        assists = player_data['A'].values
        points = player_data['PTS'].values
        games_played = player_data['GP'].values
        shots_on_goal = player_data['SOG'].values
        plus_minus = player_data['+/-'].values
    else:
        seasons = x_labels
        goals = player_data['G'].values
        assists = player_data['A'].values
        points = player_data['PTS'].values
        games_played = player_data['GP'].values
        shots_on_goal = player_data['SOG'].values
        plus_minus = player_data['+/-'].values

    # Plot Goals
    ax = axes[0, 0]
    ax.plot(seasons, goals, marker='o', label=f'{player}')
    ax.set_title(f'Goals')
    for i in range(len(goals)):
        ax.annotate(goals[i], (seasons[i], goals[i]), textcoords="offset points", xytext=(0,10), ha='center')
    ax.set_xlabel('Season')
    ax.set_ylabel('Number of goals')
    ax.legend()
    ax.grid(True)

    # Plot Assists
    ax = axes[0, 1]
    ax.plot(seasons, assists, marker='o', label=f'{player}')
    ax.set_title(f'Assists')
    for i in range(len(assists)):
        ax.annotate(assists[i], (seasons[i], assists[i]), textcoords="offset points", xytext=(0,10), ha='center')
    ax.set_xlabel('Season')
    ax.set_ylabel('Number of assists')
    ax.legend()
    ax.grid(True)

    # Plot Points
    ax = axes[0, 2]
    ax.plot(seasons, points, marker='o', label=f'{player}')
    ax.set_title(f'Points')
    for i in range(len(points)):
        ax.annotate(points[i], (seasons[i], points[i]), textcoords="offset points", xytext=(0,10), ha='center')
    ax.set_xlabel('Season')
    ax.set_ylabel('Number of points')
    ax.legend()
    ax.grid(True)

    # Plot Games Played
    ax = axes[1, 0]
    ax.plot(seasons, games_played, marker='o', label=f'{player}')
    ax.set_title(f'Games played')
    for i in range(len(games_played)):
        ax.annotate(games_played[i], (seasons[i], games_played[i]), textcoords="offset points", xytext=(0,10), ha='center')
    ax.set_xlabel('Season')
    ax.set_ylabel('Number of games')
    ax.legend()
    ax.grid(True)

    # Plot Shots on Goal
    ax = axes[1, 1]
    ax.plot(seasons, shots_on_goal, marker='o', label=f'{player}')
    ax.set_title(f'Shots on goal')
    for i in range(len(shots_on_goal)):
        ax.annotate(shots_on_goal[i], (seasons[i], shots_on_goal[i]), textcoords="offset points", xytext=(0,10), ha='center')
    ax.set_xlabel('Season')
    ax.set_ylabel('SOG')
    ax.legend()
    ax.grid(True)

    # Plot Plus/Minus
    ax = axes[1, 2]
    ax.plot(seasons, plus_minus, marker='o', label=f'{player}')
    ax.set_title(f'Plus/Minus')
    for i in range(len(plus_minus)):
        ax.annotate(plus_minus[i], (seasons[i], plus_minus[i]), textcoords="offset points", xytext=(0,10), ha='center')
    ax.set_xlabel('Season')
    ax.set_ylabel('Plus/Minus')
    ax.legend()
    ax.grid(True)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

            'Name': player,
            'Age': f"{player_data['Age'].values[0]}",

            'Games Played': f"{player_data['GP'].values[0]} -> {player_data['GP'].values[1]}",
            'Shots on Goal': f"{player_data['SOG'].values[0]} -> {player_data['SOG'].values[1]}",
            'Time on Ice': f"{player_data['ATOI'].values[0]} -> {player_data['ATOI'].values[1]}",
            'Plus/Minus': f"{player_data['+/-'].values[0]} -> {player_data['+/-'].values[1]}"
        }
    data_comparing_defenders.append(row)

Conclusion¶

We can see a pattern for each player except Lubomir Visnovsky. Each player who has played more than one season (Nemec excluded) has experienced growth over the statistics.

Lubomir Visnovsky is the only case in which his second season was statistically worse than the first. The reason behind that was his age; a player who is 24 years old is more experienced than a player who is 20 years old, which is another case in our data frame. Another reason could be struggling with injury, leading to poorer performance and dropping out of the player's rhythm. We can see a slight change in the +/- rating, where the reason could be that he played in the 3rd or 4th line more time than the 2nd line, where the first two lines scored more goals than the other.

The most striking example of potential growth is Fehervary. In his first season, he played 6 games, scored 1 point, and averaged 15:59 as time on ice. However, in his second season, he seized his opportunity to play for the Washington Capitals, playing 73 more games, scoring 16 more points, and becoming one of the most important defenders in the entire organization. This is a testament to the potential for growth and development in our players.

We can see that Nemec, who was drafted in the first round at the second overall position, played very well in his first season. It's a tradition to include young prospects in the first two lines and develop their abilities. The same thing happened in Nemec's case, where he scored more points than Fehervary, for example, in his first two seasons.

Every other player had a better second season, earning more points and more shots on goal.

The data clearly shows a correlation between increased game time and improved performance. This underscores the importance of strategic decisions in player development and the potential for even greater growth in the future.

Conclusion¶

Unlike defenders, we see a clear pattern with forwards. In almost all states, Slovak forwards improved in the second season; the only regression was recorded by Peter Stastny, who recorded fewer shots on goal, while in the +/- stats, three players regressed - Stastny, Satan, and Slafkovsky.

Interestingly, Slafkovsky, as our current best player, recorded negative stats in both seasons. This is because the best young players are drafted by the clubs doing the most negligible well in the league. Slafkovski's Montreal Canadiens team is precisely that example, failing to make the playoffs in either season. In Slafkovsky's first two seasons, Montreal finished 28th out of 32 teams and had goal deficits (the difference between goals scored and received) of -78 and -49, suggesting that the team is getting more goals than it is giving up. We can then argue that Slafkovsky's +/- stats correlate with his team's goal deficit.

Despite Peter Stastny's worse shot and +/- stats, we can notice an interesting fact: the number of points in a given season. The points of 109 and 139 are significantly higher than those of the other players examined. We can compare the first seasons of Gaborik and Stastny, who, with approximately the same number of shots and number of games, scored different numbers of points. Stastny scored 139 points in his second season on 46 goals and 93 assists, while Gaborik scored 67 points on 30 goals and 37 assists. We could debate the effectiveness of these players. Still, the most important fact for such a significant difference in points for the same number of games is that Stastny played in the 1980s and Gaborik only 20 years later. This difference is due to the evolution of hockey over so many years. In the past, more goals were scored, players scored more points, which is why Peter Stastny scored 248 points in his first two seasons. Few players have managed to do that during their early years in the NHL.

Pavol Demitra and Marian Hossa had difficult beginnings, but they gradually worked up to become major stars not only of their teams, but also of the world. Demitra scored 9 points in his first two seasons, but after 16 years in the NHL he has a total of 768 points. Hossa had a much better second season than Demitra. At the end of Hossa's career, 1,134 shone on his points tally. Hossa was the only Slovak to win 3 Stanley Cups with the Chicago Blackhawks. He was also inducted into the NHL Hall of Fame in 2020.

The point totals of the forwards improved for each player after the first season. There is a clear pattern that is showing on all players. We assumed that the points of the forwards would increase after the first season because it is a better indicator of the stats than the defensemen. Defensemen are better measured by other stats such as +/-. Then you can see if the player was more on goals scored or goals received.

Franchise data¶

In this part of the analysis, we wanted to look at historical data for all teams in the NHL. The main goal was to confirm that the league is very balanced. The secondary goal was to see if a correlation could be found between the number of playoff appearances and the number of Stanley Cups won.

Conclusion¶

The main goal was to delve into the question of whether the NHL is truly 'very balanced', as many freely available articles on the internet assert, and to underscore the significance of winning the Stanley Cup, considered the pinnacle of hockey achievement. By visualizing the PTS% parameter, a key tool in understanding the league's balance, we can determine the ratio of the number of points scored to the number of maximum points. This parameter was defined as the number of games times 2 or 3, as historically 3 points were first awarded for winning, but later 2 points were started to be awarded to make the league more attractive. The graph shows the oscillating values for each team, ranging from .475 to .627. Because the values in the graph are very close together, we can't clearly say that one particular team is better than the others. Interestingly, the Vegas Golden Knights have the highest value at .627. Although Vegas is the second newest team in the NHL (after the Seattle Kraken, which has been in the league since 2017), they have managed to win their conference twice in a short period, make it to the league finals, and even win the Stanley Cup in 2023. Regularly finishing at the top of the table and winning the Stanley Cup have significantly boosted the number on our table. Since the values in the chart are very close to 0.5, the league is balanced in a way. Several other factors contribute to this, e.g., teams that finished in the bottom ranks in the previous season are eligible to get the best draft picks.

Conclusion¶

In our analysis, we wanted to look at Stanley Cup data and see if there was a possible correlation with the number of seasons in the NHL. There are two critical pieces of data on the graph, namely the number of years in the NHL (Yrs, in blue) and the number of Stanley Cups won (St Cup, in orange). The teams with the most playoff appearances are the Montreal Canadiens, Boston Bruins, Toronto Maple Leafs, Chicago Blackhawks, Detroit Red Wings, and New York Rangers. In addition to the Rangers, these six teams have won the most Stanley Cups throughout history. This is because the Canadiens and Maple Leafs have been in the league since 1917, so they were the founders of the entire league. The Blackhawks, Bruins, Red Wings, and Rangers have only been in the league since 1924-1926. It wasn't until 1967 that new teams began to be added. Interestingly, the Vancouver Canucks and Buffalo Sabres have been in the league for 56 years but have yet to win the Stanley Cup, but the Vegas Golden Knights have been in the NHL since 2017 and have already won the title. We can see a correlation between the two analyzed stats, but a few outliers taint the correlation.

Conclusion¶

On the left graph, we can see the player's number of goals (blue) and assists (orange). On the right graph, we can see a heatmap that better shows some of the statistics in the table. Juraj Slafkovsky, a standout player, has already made his mark in two seasons, amassing an impressive 60 points in 121 games. On the heatmap we can observe the trend in +/- that occurs with young players. These players are not among the leaders of their team, so they play in the third or fourth line at the beginning, which results in a high number of minus points. The second reason may be being on a team that is not doing well, so these teams have been allowed to select their best players.

# Total points by team
query = '''
SELECT Tm, SUM(PTS) as Total_PTS
FROM jager_stats
GROUP BY Tm
'''
points_by_team = execute_query(query)

# Total goals and assists by team
query = '''
SELECT Tm, SUM(G) as Total_Goals, SUM(A) as Total_Assists
FROM jager_stats
GROUP BY Tm
'''
goals_assists_by_team = execute_query(query)

# Average points per game by team
query = '''
SELECT Tm, SUM(PTS) * 1.0 / SUM(GP) as Avg_PTS_per_GP
FROM jager_stats
GROUP BY Tm
'''
avg_pts_per_gp_by_team = execute_query(query)

# Plot all three graphs beside each other
fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(20, 6), constrained_layout=True)

Conclusion¶

For this observation, we focused on Jaromir Jagr and his performance in different teams during his career.

  • The first graph, a comprehensive representation of Jaromir Jagr's career, illustrates the total number of points he scored. Notably, Jagr's performance in the Pittsburgh Penguins team, where he had the longest tenure, shows significant fluctuation. Conversely, his shorter stints with teams like the Boston Bruins or Calgary Flames, particularly during the latter part of his career, resulted in lower values.

  • From the second graph, we can see that the mentioned player scored at least once on each team and that on each team during his career, he had more assists than goals scored.

  • The third graph has the most telling value about the player's productivity. It shows the average number of points per game for each team. Jagr had his best years with the Pittsburgh Penguins, followed by the New Jersey Devils. On the other teams, he was still close to the 0.8 points per game mark, which is a remarkable performance. We can see a significant drop in the Calgary Flames, the team where Jaromir Jagr ended his career.

  • To conclude this analysis, Jaromir Jagr was a very productive player for almost his entire career, so he has gone down in history as one of the sport's legends.

Analysis of players' sports performance about their age¶

# Function to load data, query, and plot for a player
def plot_player_comparison(csv_url, seasons, stats, stat_titles, title, colors=['blue', 'orange']):
    df = pd.read_csv(csv_url, encoding='ISO-8859-1')

    # Connect to a SQLite database (or create it)
    conn = sqlite3.connect(':memory:')  # Create an in-memory database

    # Load the DataFrame into the SQLite database
    df.to_sql('player_stats', conn, index=False, if_exists='replace')

    # Enclose column names with special characters in double quotes
    stats_quoted = [f'"{stat}"' if any(char in stat for char in ['%', '+', '/']) else stat for stat in stats]

    # Query the data for the specified seasons
    query = f'''
    SELECT Season, {", ".join(stats_quoted)}
    FROM player_stats
    WHERE Season IN ({", ".join(f"'{season}'" for season in seasons)})
    '''

    df_comparison = pd.read_sql_query(query, conn)
    conn.close()

    # Plot the comparison
    num_stats = len(stats)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, num_stats, figsize=(4 * num_stats, 5))

    for i, (stat, stat_title) in enumerate(zip(stats, stat_titles)):
        ax[i].bar(df_comparison['Season'], df_comparison[stat], color=colors)
        ax[i].set_title(stat_title)
        ax[i].set_ylabel(stat_title)

    fig.suptitle(title)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

plot_player_comparison(giordano_csv, giordano_seasons, giordano_stats, giordano_stat_titles, 'Comparison of Mark Giordano Statistics')

Conclusion¶

Our analysis was conducted with the utmost objectivity, aiming to show whether the age of hockey players has an impact on their performance, and the extent of this impact. We compared a season from a younger period of their lives with one of the most recent seasons played, ensuring a fair and objective comparison by selecting seasons with a similar number of games. We chose three players from different positions on the ice: Marc-André Fleury (goalie), Zach Parise (left-wing or forward), and Mark Giordano (defenseman). The results are clear and unbiased, showing a significant deterioration in performance for each player, indicating that age is indeed having a significant negative impact on their on-ice performance.

  • Explanation of some terms:

  1. Save percentage - expresses the percentage of shot attempts that the number of shots on goal taken by the goalkeeper as a proportion of the total number of shots on goal.

  2. Plus/Minus - If a player is on the ice when his team scores a goal when the game is tied, the player receives a +1 point. Conversely, if a player is on the ice when the opposing team scores a goal when the game is tied, the player receives -1 point.

  3. Goals Saved Above Average - If a goalie has a positive GSAA, he has saved more goals than the average goalie would have saved. Conversely, if the GSAA is negative, he has saved fewer goals than the average goalkeeper.
